  "most_recent_game": {
    "date": "2026-03-15",
    "opponent": "St John S",
    "result": "W",
    "boxscore_url": "https://www.charlotte49ers.com/sports/baseball/stats/2026/st-john-s/boxscore/19754",
    "recap_url": "https://www.charlotte49ers.com/news/2026/3/15/baseball-hudson-walks-it-off-with-the-bases-loaded-in-the-ninth",
    "recap_headline": "Charlotte",
    "recap_text": "CHARLOTTE \u2013\nTodd Hudson\ncame to the plate with the bases loaded and two outs in the bottom of the ninth inning, with Charlotte Baseball knotted with St. John's, 9-9. Hudson got a pitch he was looking for and drove it to the wall in left-center, bringing home the winning run with a walk-off single in a 10-9 victory for the 49ers on Sunday afternoon (March 15) from Hayes Stadium.\nIn a back-and-forth game that lasted over four hours and featured a steady rain throughout the final few frames, Charlotte (13-6) took its first lead of the weekend in the seventh inning when\nJohnny Sutryk\nscored from second on a wild pitch. St. John's (7-12) retook the lead in the ninth, but Hudson came through in the clutch in the home half of the last to salvage the final game of the series for the Green and White.\n\"Congratulations to St. John's on winning the series,\" head coach\nRobert Woodard\nsaid. \"That series just made our team a whole lot better. They made us work Friday in a two-run game, yesterday in a one-run game, and then made us have to walk it off on Sunday. We just wouldn't be denied. We talked yesterday after the game about playing with confidence and whatever it takes to get it done. It doesn't always have to be pretty.\nChayse Oxborrow\nonly faced two hitters but, in hindsight, those two outs were pretty big for us. Then\nTodd Hudson\ngets a big swing of the bat to win it in the ninth. It was a tough weekend but I think we'll look back at that hit in a couple of weeks and point to that moment as being a big hit for our club.\"\nHudson led the team with three hits in the game, his second multi-hit game of the weekend and his second three-hit game of the season.\nSpencer Nolan\nhad two hits for his team-leading 11th multi-hit game this year and\nCale Stricklin\nadded a pair of knocks as well.\nBoth of Nolan's and Stricklin's two hits were doubles that led to runs, combining for four of the Niners' season-high seven doubles in the game.\nSutryk had another one of the doubles, as did\nDylan Koontz\nand\nAdrian Jimenez\nfor their only hits of the game, while\nCody Gunderson\nadded a single for a team total of 12 hits, the 13th time this season the Green and White have ended a game with double-digit hits.\nHudson's walk-off single was one of two RBIs in the game for him, tying him with Nolan and DeMartino for the team lead. Jimenez and Stricklin also notched ribbies in the game.\nChayse Oxborrow\nmade his second start of the week but was only asked to get the first two outs of the game as a lefty against two lefties at the top of St. John's lineup and he did just that. Five more arms followed Oxborrow out of the bullpen, capped off by\nRyan Combs\n.\nCombs had the longest outing of his career to earn his first win as a Niner, throwing the final 4.1 innings of the game. He racked up a career-high seven strikeouts while doing so and was charged with two runs on five hits and three walks.\nBridging the gap between Oxborrow and Combs were\nSebastian Perez\n,\nAJ Camp\n,\nAdam Stanton\n, and\nChase Carson\n.\nHOW IT HAPPENED\nSt. John's got the scoring started for the third straight game with a four-run second inning. The Red Storm drew a pair of walks and a hit to bring the first one around before using a trio of sacrifice bunts and a CLT error to plate the other three.\nCharlotte got half of the runs back in the home half of the frame, in a very similar fashion by also using free passes, small-ball, and a visitor miscue.\nKoontz took first on a lead-off walk and then moved into scoring position when Gunderson was hit by a pitch. Nedry was the next batter and extended his hitting streak to 10 straight games with an RBI-single to center that scored Koontz. Sutryk was up next and laid down a sacrifice bunt, but everyone was safe and the bases were loaded after the St. John's pitcher mishandled the ball. That set up a sacrifice fly from Jimenez to bring the second and final run of the inning across for the Green and White.\nThe Red Storm added a run in the fourth inning, again taking advantage of a Niner error, but Charlotte answered again with two more in the bottom of the inning.\nHudson drew a walk to start the frame and moved up to third when Jimenez poked one the other way into the corner in right. A sacrifice fly from Stricklin scored Hudson and then Jimenez came home when Nolan traded places with him after roping one down the third-base line, pulling the Niners within one, 5-4.\nSt. John's scored two more in the fifth from a trio of hits and once again the Niners had a response, this time in the sixth, to bring the game level for the first time since the second inning.\nStricklin started it off with a double off the top of the wall in left-center. The ball bounced off the top of the yellow line that rings the top of the outfield wall but fell back into play, leaving Stricklin standing on second with a double instead of trotting home with a home run. The lineup then flipped over for Nolan, who drew a walk to put runners on the corners, followed by Nedry wearing one to load them up.\nDeMartino stepped to the plate with the bags juiced and sent one back from where it came, driving in two with a single up the middle. Nedry went from first to third on the single and then came home on a wild pitch to tie the game at seven after six.\nCharlotte took its first lead of the weekend after the stretch in the seventh on another wild pitch from the SJU battery. Sutryk drew a walk to lead the frame off and then stole second. Jimenez also worked a walk to put a pair on. Nedry was at the dish with two gone when a wild offering missed up and in and eluded the St. John's catcher. The catcher couldn't find the ball as it rolled towards the Niners' dugout, allowing Sutryk to score from second. Jimenez ended up at third on the wild pitch and Nedry eventually drew a walk in the plate appearance before stealing second to put a pair of insurance runs in scoring position, but a fly ball to left held CLT to a single run.\nThe Green and White had two more in scoring position again in the eighth inning but couldn't bring either around, taking a one-run lead into the ninth. St. John's was down to its final out with the tying run on third and kept the game alive, finding a hole through the left side to tie the game and then doubling to the wall in left to retake the lead.\nCharlotte came to the plate down by one in the ninth with its nine-hole hitter but Stricklin acted like a middle-of-the-lineup slugger by beginning the inning with his second double of the day.\nJuan Rivera\ncame in to run for him and came home when Nolan pulled his second double of the day down the third-base line. Nedry walked and Koontz was hit by a pitch for the second time to load them up in the last, with the winning run only 90 feet away.\nThe Niners got down to their final out when Hudson stepped to the dish but he delivered, smoking one to the gap in left to bring home Nolan and end the weekend on a high note.\nUP NEXT\nCharlotte has a pair of midweek games next week, beginning with a game on Tuesday (March 17) at South Carolina. Originally scheduled for 6:30 p.m., first pitch has been moved up to 4 p.m. due to forecasted temperatures."
  },
